{"default_url":null,"content":{"state":0,"taskInstructions":null,"references":[],"isTaskInstructionsVisible":true,"isCommentMandatory":false,"fields":[],"masterFinding":{"id":17051124,"exploitInstructions":"","verificationInstructions":"<b>Verification Instructions</b>\n\nUse the forgot password functionality (if available) to see if new password is sent in an email.\n\nIf the password meets complexity requirements and users are required to change it after one use, the finding should not be reported. Strong OTP is as strong as a reset token.\n\n<b>Reporting Requirements</b>\n<ol><li>Show forgot password functionality</li>\n<li>Show the email containing a password - redact the password</li>\n</ol>\n","remediationInstructions":"Implement the following password recovery process:\n<ol><li>Allow users to start the password recovery process by entering their email address on the reset page.</li>\n<li>Require users to fill in a captcha and return a message stating &quot;Your request has been processed&quot; for both valid and non-existing user accounts.</li>\n<li>Send an email to the user containing a URL with a unique, one-time token. The token links the password reset request to the user's account. The token should expire in 15 minutes or less.</li>\n<li>The password reset page should not authenticate the user to the application; it should only allow a password reset.</li>\n<li>Require correct answers to security questions on the password reset page.</li>\n<li>Invalidate the token after it has been used once.</li>\n</ol>\n","name":"Weak Password Reset - Password in Email","sourceId":"M:30ca6c46-abb2-e211-b9cf-001e4f12001e","severity":"Medium","businessImpact":"Were an attacker able to access the victim's email, it could be possible to access the affected application by using these credentials via the password reset functionality.","description":"Passwords are sent in clear text via email to users during the password reset process.\n"}}}